<p>

Lindroth has ninety-six screen credits beginning with a role in the <it>Battle of Pottsburg Bridge</it> in 1912. Other films she appeared in include <it>A Battle of Wits</it> (1912), <it>The Menace of Fate</it> (1914), <it>The Black Crook</it> (1916), <it>Shadows of Suspicion</it> (1919), <it>The Way of a Maid</it> (1921), <it>Unguarded Women</it> (1924), and <it>The Song and Dance Man</it> (1926).</p>
<p>

Lindroth gave up acting around 1936 and became associated with the <nongovernmental_organization wordnetid="108009834" confidence="0.8">
<denomination wordnetid="108146782" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../309/125309.xml">
Christian Science</link></denomination>
</nongovernmental_organization>
 Benevolent Association in <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../150/1308150.xml">
Chestnut Hill, Massachusetts</link>. She retired from this philanthropic work in 1953.</p>

